Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# data.shape[0] will give us the number of rows in the dataset
# selecting the instances where missing value is greater than 0
pd.DataFrame({'Count':df.isnull().sum()[df.isnull().sum()>0],'Percentage':(df.isnull().sum()[df.isnull().sum()>0]/df.shape[0])*100})
Out[18]:
Count Percentage
rating 736 38.778

Comment:

  • As we have a high percentage of missing values (38% in our case) and the column may contain outliers, using the mean method for imputing missing values is appropriate. The mean provides a measure of central, tendency that considers all available values in the column, including non-missing values

  • Although the mean can be influenced by outliers, it still provides a reasonable estimation in most cases. By replacing missing values with the mean, we can preserve the overall distribution of the data. This approach will also provide a more reliable estimation of the missing values while minimizing the impact of outliers on the imputations

In [19]:
df['rating'] = df['rating'].fillna(value= df['rating'].mean())

restaurant_data = df.groupby('restaurant_name').agg({'rating': ['count', 'mean']})

# Filter the restaurants fulfilling the criteria
promotional_restaurants = restaurant_data[(restaurant_data['rating']['count'] > 50) & (restaurant_data['rating']['mean'] > 4)]

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [43]:
# Write the code here
# Calculating the revenue generated by charging 25% on orders > 20 dollars
rev_25_percent = df[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20]['cost_of_the_order'].sum() * 0.25

# Calculating the revenue generated by charging 15% on orders > 5 dollars
rev_15_percent = df[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20)]['cost_of_the_order'].sum() * 0.15

# Calculating the net revenue by summing up the revenues from both charges
net_revenue = rev_25_percent + rev_15_percent

print(f"The net revenue generated by the company: {net_revenue}")

The net revenue generated by the company: 6166.303

Observations:¶

  • The company generates a net revenue of $6166.303 by charging restaurants a percentage of the order cost. This revenue is obtained by applying different percentages based on the order cost thresholds

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

# Write the code here
# Calculating the total time for each order
df['total_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']

# Filtering the orders that take more than 60 minutes
orders_above_60_minutes = df[df['total_time'] > 60]

# Calculating the percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes
percentage_above_60_minutes = "{:.2f}".format((orders_above_60_minutes.shape[0] / df.shape[0]) * 100)

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusion:¶

The Dataset extracted from the food aggregator company FoodHub who offers access to multiple restaurants and it has been analysed to understand the trend of categories which can be beneficial for business. With the help of descriptive analysis and visualisations, some insights have been drawn as below:

Around 70% of cuisine orders indicates higher on weekends than weekdays

American cuisine is often preferred by the customers

Most of the restaurants have received ratings above average and 75% of users have given ratings greater than 4

On average, it takes approximately 24 minutes for the delivery person to deliver the food package from the time the order is placed. It can be used to assess the efficiency and speed of the delivery service provided by the restaurants or organisations

There higher frequency of lower cost orders and exhibits some skewness towards lower cost values

On average, orders are delivered faster on weekends compared to weekdays

The majority of orders have relatively shorter preparation times

Data is relatively consistent and does not contain extreme values that could potentially skew the analysis or affect the interpretation of the results

Recommendations:¶

The company can consider offering promotional deals or discounts specifically on weekends, as the analysis shows that there is a higher percentage of cuisine orders on weekends. This can help attract more customers and increase sales during weekends.

The average delivery time indicates a reasonable efficiency in the delivery service. However, the company can further focus on optimizing the delivery process to ensure timely and faster deliveries, particularly on weekdays where the average delivery time is slightly higher. This can help enhance customer experience and satisfaction.

The analysis shows a higher frequency of lower cost orders. The company can conduct further analysis on the cost structure, profit margins, and customer preferences to identify opportunities for pricing optimization, cost reduction, and net revenue generation.

Although the dataset exhibits relatively consistent data without significant outliers, it is still important for the company to monitor and identify any potential outliers in the future. Outliers can provide valuable insights or indicate potential issues that require attention, such as unusually long delivery times or extremely high-cost orders.

As we have a high percentage of Not Rated indications, encourage customers to rate their orders by offering incentives or rewards. This can be in the form of discounts on future orders, loyalty points, or exclusive offers. Providing a clear benefit for rating orders can motivate customers to actively provide feedback.

This will also help enhance the overall customer experience, gather valuable feedback, and improve the accuracy of ratings, leading to a more reliable and informative platform for both customers and restaurants.
